The kernel primitives revisited.

From notebook one, remember that docker composes existing linux kernel features rather than inventing isolation. Here is a quick reminder of what each one buys you. Namespaces isolate views of the system, the process-I-D, mount, network, inter-process communication, hostname, user, and control-group views, and they are what make a container feel like a container. Control groups account for and limit resources, the see-pee-you, memory, disk, and process counts that notebook three covered. Capabilities slice the all-powerful root account into around forty individual privileges, so you can hand out exactly one rather than all of them. Secure computing mode lets you allow-list or block-list specific system calls, and docker's default profile already blocks around fifty dangerous ones. And the mandatory-access-control systems, app-armor and ess-ee-linux, sit on top of ordinary file permissions, with docker shipping a sensible default profile.

There is one more worth calling out, user namespaces, which map the user-I-Ds inside a container to different user-I-Ds on the host, so that root inside the container can be an ordinary unprivileged user outside it.

The encouraging part is that the configuration docker gives a container out of the box is already much tighter than running the same process directly on the host. It drops more than half of the capabilities, blocks around fifty system calls with the default secure-computing profile, and applies the default app-armor profile where app-armor is available. But much tighter than nothing is not the same as tight enough for production, and the rest of this notebook is really about how much further you should turn each of these dials.
